articles.author: Reuters
articles.description: Russian-installed authorities in Crimea said on Saturday they planned to sell about 100 Ukrainian properties, including one belonging to Ukrainian President Volodymyr Zelenskiy.
articles.title: Russian-installed Crimea authorities to sell Ukrainian properties

articles.author: Reuters
articles.description: Ukrainian business magnate Ihor Kolomoisky has been served with notice of a third set of allegations following his detention on suspicion of fraud and money laundering, the Security Service of Ukraine (SBU) said on Friday.
articles.title: Ukraine security agency confirms new allegations against magnate Kolomoisky

articles.author: Renee Maltezou
articles.description: Greek Prime Minister Kyriakos Mitsotakis is expected to announce state reforms and relief measures in a keynote speech on Saturday, days after a devastating rainstorm killed at least 17 people, sources said.
articles.title: Greek PM to call for reforms, fiscal prudence after deadly storm - sources

articles.author: Rozanna Latiff, Danial Azhar
articles.description: A string of dropped corruption cases in Malaysia has raised questions over Prime Minister Anwar Ibrahim's commitment to fighting graft, with lawmakers and analysts warning it could risk alienating voters, deepen divisions within the ruling coalition, and jeopardise his reform agenda.
articles.title: Analysis: Malaysia PM Anwar's reform agenda in doubt as allies freed from graft charges

articles.author: Reuters
articles.description: Thousands of mourners gathered in eastern South Africa on Saturday for the state funeral of Mangosuthu Buthelezi.
articles.title: Mourners gather in South African for funeral of controversial Zulu prince Buthelezi

articles.author: Reuters
articles.description: A man was arrested in the earlier hours of Saturday morning after being spotted climbing into the Royal Mews adjacent to Buckingham Palace in London, police said.
articles.title: Man arrested climbing into Royal Mews by Buckingham Palace

articles.author: Reuters
articles.description: Germany has decided to keep taking in migrants and refugees arriving in Italy, the interior minister said late on Friday, two days after it announced the suspension of a voluntary agreement with Rome to receive new arrivals.
articles.title: Germany says it will keep taking in migrants from Italy after all

articles.author: Joseph White
articles.description: The United Auto Workers (UAW) union said on Thursday workers would walk off the job at three Detroit Three factories at midnight, barring a last-minute agreement, setting up the most ambitious U.S. industrial labor action in decades.
articles.title: U.S. auto workers target Detroit Three plants for historic strike

articles.author: Julia Payne, Alan Charlish
articles.description: Poland, Slovakia and Hungary announced their own restrictions on Ukrainian grain imports on Friday after the European Commission decided not to extend its ban on imports into Ukraine's five EU neighbours.
articles.title: Poland, Hungary, Slovakia to introduce own bans on Ukraine grains

articles.author: Balazs Koranyi, Francesco Canepa
articles.description: European Central Bank President Christine Lagarde seized the mobile phones of her fellow policymakers at this week's meeting and rebuked them for leaking crucial information ahead of a policy decision, two sources told Reuters.
articles.title: Lagarde seized ECB colleagues' handsets to prevent leaks
